{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472829"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:01:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:01:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1556"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1556"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.52,0.08,0.03,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1556"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90805"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1556"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1556"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74886"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"827"},{"type":"tags","id":"2083"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"11615"},{"type":"tags","id":"11616"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31120"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90805"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-week-old infant presents with parental concern of a \u201cfunny looking belly-button\u201d. He was delivered vaginally at 39+3 with no birthing complications. He has been well since birth and his umbilical cord fell off one week ago (at age two weeks). On examination there is an obvious swelling about the umbilicus (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Omphalitis","Umbilical granuloma","Delayed cord separation","Leukocyte adhesion deficiency","Umbilical polyp"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe picture shows the infant has an \u003Cstrong\u003Eumbilical granuloma\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the most common cause of umbilical site \u201cooze\u201d in infants and is composed of residual capillary and fibroblast cells. Parents can be reassured, although if there are problems with significant bleeding at the site, silver nitrate cautery or even surgical excision may be offered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUmbilical polyps\u003C/strong\u003E may look similar but are often larger, and have a brighter red appearance. They are composed of omphalomesenteric duct embryological remnants, and further work-up for these remnants is warranted with surgical excision and histology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOmphalitis \u003C/strong\u003Einvolves infection of the umbilical cord stump, can present with a septic appearing baby, usually occurs on day five to nine of life, and often requires admission for bloods, wound swabs and antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDelayed cord separation\u003C/strong\u003E is defined as umbilical cord separation after three weeks of life. This has some associations with defects in neutrophil function, such as in \u003Cstrong\u003Eleukocyte adhesion deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Umbilical granulomas are a common, benign cause of ooze from the umbilical site of an infant"],"references":["Srinivas Jois R, Rao S. Management of umbilical granuloma in infants: A systematic review of randomised controlled trials. Aust J Gen Pract. 2021;50(8):589-594. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2021/august/management-of-umbilical-granuloma-in-infants","Kliegman, Robert. Nelson Textbook of Pediatrics. Edition 21. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier, 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74886"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1556"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15944"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15944"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/223d8155-5e39-4043-9b4b-3acf299735fb.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/223d8155-5e39-4043-9b4b-3acf299735fb.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":448,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74886"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T16:14:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T16:14:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1556"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90805"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"}